# Lin Language TODO
# Format: [ ] pending  [/] in progress  [x] done
# Tiers: 🔴 blocking  🟡 important  🟢 nice-to-have

# Architecture reference (PICR — Reversible Polarized Interaction Combinators):
#   pic.graph  → abstract combinator graph (γ⁺ γ⁻ δ H L ω R + boundaries)
#   pic.reduce → scheduling-aware reduction ops (annihilate/dup/uncompute/log_state/
#                                                 fire_op/reverse_vector/log_bond)
#   pic.runtime→ CPU/GPU dispatch (cpu_dispatch, gpu_batch, gpu_batch_reverse,
#                                  uncompute_sweep, sync_point)
#
# Node set (7 nodes):
#   γ⁺  Constructor   principal(+), aux(left, right)
#   γ⁻  Destructor    principal(-), aux(left, right)
#   δ   Duplicator    principal(*), aux(left, right)
#   H   History       replaces ε; folds dead subgraphs into boundary history log
#   L   Log-Bond      passive ghost deposited at annihilation splice sites
#   ω   Operation     principal(+/-), aux(inputs..., outputs...)
#   R   Reverse-Vec   signal node; propagates backward rewrites through subgraph
#
# 4 Rules (reversible form):
#   Rule 1 — Reversible Annihilation (γ⁺ ⋈ γ⁻ → splice + deposit L-bond)
#   Rule 2 — Duplication (δ ⋈ γ⁺; reverse requires sync barrier at δ on backward pass)
#   Rule 3 — Reversible Uncomputation (R signal replaces ε sweep; runs subgraph backward)
#   Rule 4 — Congruence (inside boundaries; merge node carries origins attr for reverse split)
# Rules should be mostly user-defined via a lookup table.
# Goal: CPU, GPU, and high-perf GPU shaders — unified reversible pipeline via MLIR.
#
# 4 Invariants:
#   1. Linearity of principal ports
#   2. Boundary interface consistency
#   3. Confluence
#   4. Conservation of Topological Information — no rewrite may reduce graph information
#      entropy; every destructive step logs its delta or pairs with an R signal

## 🔴 Tier 0 — Architecture (foundational correctness)

# CPU/GPU Unification Strategy:
# The goal is to implement every reduction rule ONCE in the target-independent
# pic.reduce dialect using scf + arith + memref dialects (no llvm.*), then rely
# on MLIR's existing conversion passes to lower to:
#   • LLVM IR (CPU via ConvertToLLVMPass)
#   • SPIR-V / PTX (GPU via ConvertToSPIRVPass / GPU dialect)
# This means A1b is the central fix — all other "b" items are cleanup work that
# becomes natural once the reduction logic lives in the right dialect.
# Items 31, A4b, 21b, A2b, A3b are all sub-problems of finishing A1b correctly.
#
# Three architectural constraints hold throughout pic.reduce for unification:
#   C1. STATIC OPCODE DISPATCH — no function pointers (SPIR-V has none)
#   C2. HOST-ALLOCATED ARENA   — no malloc inside kernels (illegal on GPU)
#   C3. ω GPU ELIGIBILITY      — payloads restricted to SPIR-V-legal dialects

[ ] C1. Replace indirect dispatch with static opcode switch 🔴
        # Architecture constraint: SPIR-V has no function pointers. The current
        # `dispatch_user_op` model (hash → function pointer call) is CPU-only and
        # will silently be dead code on any GPU path.
        # See Architecture.md "CPU/GPU Unified Execution Model" §1.
        - Rule table entry: (typeA, labelA, typeB, labelB, opcode_index: i32)
          opcode_index assigned at compile time from the ordered list of registered rules
        - Reduction kernel: one scf switch over opcode_index with one case per rule
          (not a hash lookup through a function pointer)
        - mlir-op declarations compile into a case in the static switch, not a separate
          LLVM function reached through dispatch_user_op
        - On CPU: scf.switch lowers to a jump table (identical performance)
        - On GPU: scf.switch lowers to spirv.Switch (legal, portable)
        - Prerequisite: A1b (must live in pic.reduce, not hand-rolled LLVM)

[ ] C2. Formalize host-allocated arena — no malloc inside kernels 🔴
        # Architecture constraint: GPU device code cannot call malloc/free.
        # The current main() mallocs 128MB for net/queue at startup (line 1733-1744)
        # but this is expressed as llvm.call @malloc inside the kernel entry, which
        # is legal on CPU and silently wrong when the same IR targets a GPU kernel.
        # See Architecture.md "CPU/GPU Unified Execution Model" §2.
        - All arena allocations (net, queue, alloc counter) must happen on the HOST
          before kernel launch, expressed as memref.alloc() in the host wrapper
        - Inside pic.reduce: alloc_node = memref.atomic_rmw(Add, 1, alloc[0])
          followed by memref.store into arena[idx] — zero malloc calls
        - pic.runtime.gpu_batch receives (arena, queue, alloc) as memref args;
          on GPU these become StorageBuffer descriptors; on CPU they are flat pointers
        - Prerequisite: A1b, A4b

[ ] C3. ω GPU eligibility check at mlir-op registration time 🟡
        # Architecture constraint: GPU payloads may only use SPIR-V-legal dialects
        # (arith, math, index, vector, memref/StorageBuffer). Any payload containing
        # llvm.*, func.call, or I/O ops must be marked cpu_only.
        # See Architecture.md "CPU/GPU Unified Execution Model" §3.
        - At mlir-op registration: walk the payload ops; check each op's dialect against
          the GPU-legal allowlist (arith, math, index, vector, memref)
        - If any op is GPU-illegal: set flags bit cpu_only in the rule table entry
        - Routing check at dispatch time: test cpu_only flag before gpu_batch enqueue
        - @gpu annotation on a cpu_only op: emit compile-time error (not silent skip)
        - @cpu annotation on a GPU-eligible op: valid override, routes to CPU
        - Enables: std library to automatically route `print`, `malloc` etc. to CPU
          and `add`, `mul`, `sqrt` etc. to GPU without user annotation
        - Prerequisite: C1 (rule table needs a flags field), A1b

[x] A1. pic.reduce pass: implement reduction rules in target-independent MLIR
        - PicReduceToRuntimePass walks pic.graph functions
        - Emits pic_reduce.annihilate/duplicate/erase/fire_op ops
        - Handles boundary merge (B2)

[ ] A1b. PicReduceToRuntimePass body is an empty stub 🔴
        # LoweringPasses.cpp:286 — runOnOperation() is literally `{}`.
        # The pass struct exists but performs zero work. All actual pic.reduce → runtime
        # lowering is done inline inside PicRuntimeToLLVMPass, which skips the intermediate
        # dialect entirely and emits LLVM IR directly. This collapses the three-dialect
        # pipeline to effectively two, breaking the target-independence guarantee.
        # THIS IS THE ROOT CAUSE of the CPU/GPU divergence: fixing it makes CPU and GPU
        # share 100% of the reduction logic with zero duplication.
        - Implement PicReduceToRuntimePass::runOnOperation() using scf + arith + memref
          dialects ONLY (no llvm.*). Emit pic.runtime ops (alloc_node, link, push_redex).
        - The redex dispatch loop, polarity decode, rule table lookup, and annihilation/
          duplication/erasure rules all go here — once — in target-independent MLIR.
        - PicRuntimeToLLVMPass then becomes a thin mechanical conversion of pic.runtime ops
          to llvm.* for CPU; a separate PicRuntimeToSPIRVPass does the same for GPU.
        - Unblocks: item 31 (unified pipeline), A4b (queue safety), 21b (multi-threading)

[x] A2. Rule lookup table (user-extensible dispatch)
        - APPROVED: table keyed on (agentType_A, label_A, agentType_B, label_B)
        - Runtime struct pic.reduction_rule with fields: typeA, labelA, typeB, labelB, handler
        - Default rules: annihilate, duplicate, erase, fire_op, merge_boundary
        - register_rule() runtime function for std library to add custom rules
        - Replace if-else CondBrOp chain with table lookup loop
        - Same table, different lowering for CPU (LLVM) vs GPU (SPIR-V)

[ ] A2b. Rule table capacity is hardcoded to 100 entries 🟡
        # LoweringPasses.cpp:896 — `maxRules = 100`. The array is statically allocated
        # at 300 i32 slots (3 fields × 100 rules). Silently drops rules beyond 100.
        # Also: register_rule signature is (op: i32, type: i32, impl: i32) — only 3 fields.
        # The spec calls for (typeA, labelA, typeB, labelB, handler) = 5 fields.
        # The current 3-field scheme conflates labelA+typeA into one key, losing precision.
        # FIX STRATEGY: implement the rule table in pic.reduce (memref<Nx5xi32>),
        # not as a hand-rolled LLVM global. MLIR's memref lowering handles both targets.
        - Expand rule table entry to 5 fields: (typeA, labelA, typeB, labelB, impl)
        - Implement as a memref in pic.reduce — lowers to LLVM global (CPU) and
          SPIR-V storage buffer (GPU) automatically via existing conversion passes
        - Update register_rule() and lookup_rule() to use memref ops, not llvm.load/store
        - Prerequisite: A1b

[x] A3. Fix γ⁺/γ⁻ encoding for function agents
        - A3 FIX: γ⁺/γ⁻ are both NODE_CON=1 per PIC spec
        - Polarity is in port value, not node type
        - Collapsed checkBeta block - function app is now standard annihilation
        - Collapsed isEither block - ω(branch)⋈num covered by rules
        - Simplified dispatch to just annihilation vs commutation
        - Now uses rule lookup table from A2

[ ] A3b. Polarity is stored in meta word bits [31:30] but decoded inconsistently 🟡
        # LoweringPasses.cpp:193 — metaValue = (polVal << 30) | (val & 0xFFFFFF)
        # LoweringPasses.cpp:1228-1229 — worker reads polA = metaA32 >> 30
        # This encoding works for polarity values 0,1,2 fitting in 2 bits. But:
        # (a) The alloc_node op takes an I8Attr:$type but the type byte is unused in the
        #     actual node layout — the meta word is set separately via set_port. The
        #     alloc_node type argument and the meta word are inconsistent (different paths).
        # (b) The duplication rule (commPath, line 1321) copies auxA1/auxA2 into BOTH new
        #     nodes verbatim without checking if they point into already-live redexes.
        #     Specifically: `allocNode(polA, labelA, auxA1, auxA2)` is called twice for a1
        #     and a2, giving them the same aux ports, which violates port linearity.
        # FIX STRATEGY: once A1b is done, the meta-word is encoded/decoded inside
        # pic.runtime ops (alloc_node, get_port, set_port) not raw LLVM shifts. The
        # arith dialect expresses bit manipulation portably across CPU and GPU.
        - Audit alloc_node: reconcile I8Attr:$type with the meta-word encoding;
          make the type field the single source of truth (remove set_port(3, meta))
        - Fix duplication commutation in A1b: new δ nodes get fresh placeholder ports,
          not copies of the original aux values (see HVM paper Rule 2 diagram)
        - Prerequisite: A1b

[x] A4. Boundary [ ] lowering
        - BoundaryOp now lowered in PicReduceToRuntimePass
        - getNextBoundaryId() for unique boundary tracking
        - B1: containment - effect bubbling via wire polarity
        - B2: merge_boundary op when boundaries meet
        - B3: collapse deferred to runtime E-graph hashing

[ ] A4b. Redex queue is unbounded and single-producer / multi-consumer unsafe 🟡
        # LoweringPasses.cpp:1172-1173 — the worker does atomic fetch-add on wHead to
        # claim a redex slot, but wTail is only incremented non-atomically by linkPorts
        # (line 1218). Under concurrent reduction (item 20's CAS model), two threads can
        # both see hV < tV and claim the same slot. The queue size is also fixed at the
        # malloc'd 128MB chunk with no overflow detection.
        # FIX STRATEGY: in A1b, express the redex queue as a memref<Nxi64> and the
        # head/tail counters as atomic memref scalars. scf.for + arith.addi expresses
        # the pop loop; memref.atomic_rmw expresses the CAS. Both lower to correct CPU
        # (llvm.atomicrmw) and GPU (spirv.AtomicIAdd) code without divergence.
        - Add a bounds check in the redex pop path (clamp myIdx to queue capacity)
        - Express head/tail as memref.atomic_rmw in pic.reduce (not direct LLVM atomic)
        - Document and enforce MPMC discipline: both push and pop must be atomic
        - Prerequisite: A1b

[ ] A5. PICR node set extension: H, L, R nodes in pic.graph dialect 🔴
        # Foundational prerequisite for all reversibility. Blocks A6, A7, A8, item 18, item 21.
        - Add agentType values: HIS (H), LOG (L), RVEC (R) to PicGraph_AgentOp
        - H node: no principal interaction; accumulates a history_chain attribute pointing
          into the enclosing boundary's history log; replaces ε for boundary-scoped GC
        - L node: passive, no ports fired; carries {node_a_idx, node_b_idx} back-pointer
          to the originating γ⁺/γ⁻ pair; sits on spliced wires after annihilation
        - R node: principal(*), aux(next) — propagates through a subgraph forcing each
          encountered node to execute its rewrite rule in reverse
        - Update PicGraphDialect.td and PicGraphDialect.cpp
        - Update node encoding constants in LoweringPasses.cpp (NODE_HIS, NODE_LOG, NODE_RVEC)
        - Add to A2 rule lookup table: default dispatch entries for H, L, R interactions

[ ] A6. Reversible Annihilation — L-bond deposition in pic.reduce 🔴
        # Prerequisite: A5
        - Modify PicReduceToRuntimePass: annihilate now emits pic_reduce.log_bond at splice
          site instead of vanishing the γ⁺/γ⁻ pair entirely
        - Add PicReduce_LogBondOp to PicReduceDialect.td
          arguments: (node_a_idx: i32, node_b_idx: i32) — enough to reconstruct the pair
        - L node sits passively on the spliced wires; carries the log_bond payload
        - Forward path cost: O(1) — same as classic annihilation plus one extra node slot
        - Reverse path: R signal hitting an L node reads the payload and reconstructs the
          γ⁺/γ⁻ pair, restoring the original wiring
        - Invariant 4 enforcement: this is the mechanism that satisfies "log your delta"

[ ] A7. Reversible Uncomputation — R signal propagation (replaces ε sweep) 🔴
        # Prerequisite: A5, A6
        # This replaces item 18 (Node GC / arena reset) for boundary-scoped memory.
        - Add PicReduce_ReverseVectorOp to PicReduceDialect.td
        - Add pic_reduce.uncompute op: inverts a specific node pair using its log payload
        - Add pic_reduce.log_state op: pushes a structural delta token to the boundary history log
        - R signal dispatch rules added to worker_thread (alongside existing annihilation dispatch):
            R ⋈ γ⁺  → R on each aux port
            R ⋈ γ⁻  → R on each aux port
            R ⋈ ω   → cancel op, R on each aux port
            R ⋈ δ   → R on each aux port (sync barrier required — see item 20b)
            R ⋈ L   → read log_bond payload, reconstruct γ⁺/γ⁻, continue R propagation
            R ⋈ H   → replay H's history log backward, free chain, dissolve H node
        - Outside boundaries: ε erasure path kept as the fast non-logging fallback
        - Inside boundaries: R signal is emitted instead of ε when a branch becomes dead

[ ] A8. Boundary history log and B4 Reversible Boundary Cycle 🔴
        # Prerequisite: A4, A5, A6, A7. Also requires item 21 (E-graph congruence) for
        # the origins attribute to be well-defined.
        - Extend PicGraph_BoundaryOp with two new fields:
            history_log: region — linear sequence of log tokens (structural deltas)
            origins: attr   — maps each congruence-merged node to its source wire set
        - Implement B4 — Reversible Boundary Cycle:
            1. Isolate:    computation executes inside [ ]; H nodes accumulate history log
            2. Exfiltrate: answer wire crosses boundary interface to outer scope via B1
            3. Rollback:   outer scope sends success token into boundary;
                           boundary triggers internal uncompute loop (runs log backward)
            4. Dissolve:   empty boundary undergoes B3; dissolves at zero thermodynamic cost
        - Add pic_runtime.uncompute_sweep op to PicRuntimeDialect.td
        - uncompute_sweep: reads boundary history_log and drives R-signal propagation in reverse
          order; fully parallel, SIMD-shaped identically to the forward pass

