        - LOWER:    lowerExpression emits RegistryOp(name, payload) + ω agent ✅
        - REGISTRY: RegistryOp collection exists in LoweringPasses.cpp (STR_ only) ⚠️
                    Fix: extend to collect non-STR_ entries from mlir-op declarations
        - DISPATCH: switch-case payload cloning machinery exists and works ✅
                    (used by std lib ops; user ops just need to reach it)
        - RUNTIME:  ω(+, f) ⋈ ω(-, f) → fires cloned MLIR payload for label f
        - Connects to A2: user-defined mlir-op rules register to the lookup table

[ ] 4b. mlir-op inverse payload support 🟢
        # PICR extension to item 4. Prerequisite: A7.
        - Extend RegistryOp / mlir-op parser syntax to accept an optional `inverse:` block
        - inverse: block contains an MLIR snippet executed by pic_reduce.uncompute during
          the reverse pass when this ω's op is being uncomputed
        - Standard library ops (add, fadd, mul, etc.) ship with trivial inverses (sub, fneg, etc.)
        - Without an inverse: block, uncompute falls back to structural graph reversal only
          (correct but may leave garbage; inverse: block enables clean algebraic reversal)

[ ] 4c. `add` and `either` are hardcoded as non-free-vars in findFreeVars 🟡
        # Lowering.c:199-201 — findFreeVars() has:
        #   bool is_builtin = (callee == "add") || (callee == "either");
        # This means `add` and `either` are silently exempted from free variable capture.
        # This is a spec violation: the language has zero built-in ops (see Architecture.md
        # philosophy section). If `add` is defined in std/math.lin and imported, it should
        # be captured as a free variable exactly like any other identifier.
        # Consequence: closures that capture `add` from an outer scope may fail to thread
        # the binding through the auxiliary ports of the enclosing γ⁺ node.
        - Remove the is_builtin exemption from findFreeVars()
        - Ensure std library ops resolve correctly as env_fetch'd values, not magic names
        - Add test/test_closure_capture_add.lin: closure that captures an aliased add

[ ] 4d. proj_N field access emits a δ(pair) node but wires p2 (right) to nothing 🟡
        # Lowering.c:662-671 — field access (AST_FIELD_ACCESS) emits a delta node with
        # label "proj_N", links p1 → base, and returns p0. But p2 (the other projection)
        # is never linked to anything. This leaves a dangling port in the graph, violating
        # the linearity invariant: every port must connect to exactly one wire.
        # When either .0 or .1 is accessed but not the other, the unused projection
        # must be connected to an H (history) / ε (eraser) node to satisfy linearity.
        - After emitting the proj_N agent, check if the complementary port will be used
        - If not (single field access), attach an ε (or H inside boundary) to p2
        - Add test/test_field_access_linearity.lin: access .0 only, verify no dangling port

