[ ] 31. Unified CPU/GPU reduction pipeline via pic.reduce 🔴
          # Umbrella item. Completed by finishing A1b + A2b + A3b + A4b.
          # The strategy: one pic.reduce pass, two thin conversion passes.
          #
          #   pic.reduce (scf + arith + memref)
          #      └─> PicRuntimeToLLVMPass   → LLVM IR  → CPU binary
          #      └─> PicRuntimeToSPIRVPass  → SPIR-V   → Vulkan GPU kernel
          #
          # Every reduction rule (annihilate, duplicate, erase, fire_op, merge_boundary,
          # and all PICR ops) is written once in pic.reduce and shared by both targets.
          # The conversion passes are mechanical: pic_runtime.alloc_node → llvm.call malloc
          # on CPU, → spirv.AccessChain on GPU. No reduction logic is duplicated.
          - A1b: implement PicReduceToRuntimePass with scf/arith/memref (see A1b)
          - A2b: rule table as memref, portable across CPU and GPU (see A2b)
          - A3b: fix meta-word encoding and duplication rule in target-independent ops (A3b)
          - A4b: atomic queue via memref.atomic_rmw, safe under MPMC (see A4b)
          - Add PicRuntimeToSPIRVPass as a thin sibling of PicRuntimeToLLVMPass
          - Retire the hand-rolled LLVM builder code in PicRuntimeToLLVMPass; keep only
            the mechanical dialect conversion (pic_runtime.* → llvm.*)

